00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
So we're shifting gears today.  We're going to talk about molecular  

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:08.000
evolution, i.e.  how do we understand how species  

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
evolve, how do we understand a lot about ourselves,   

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:17.000
how human evolution is taking place over the last couple hundred  

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.000
thousand years.  And traditionally,   

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:25.000
evolution has been the purview of people who study the morphology of  

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:29.000
organisms, and when I talk about morphology, obviously I'm talking  

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:34.000
about shape and form.  And by comparing organisms,   

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.000
starting already 250 years ago,  one began to develop hierarchies of  

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.000
how different organisms on the planet are related to one another.   

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:47.000
You've seen this, undoubtedly, in high school biology.   

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:51.000
This is the study of phylogeny,  and phylogeny has traditionally been  

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.000
figured out by comparing the phenotypes, the morphologies of  

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.000
adults, sometimes embryonic development, and on that basis,   

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.000
attempting to extrapolate back in evolutionary time,   

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
about the relatedness of different organisms, one to the other.   

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:14.000
And in so doing,  one has been able to create,   

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:18.000
for example, family trees, here's something that Charles Darwin was  

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
already interested in,  the various kinds of finches on the  

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:27.000
Galapagos Islands off Peru,  in the Pacific.  And here, one is  

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:31.000
beginning to organize different bird species on the basis of whether  

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:35.000
they're more closely or less closely related to one another,   

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:39.000
and to draw pedigrees, which,  one imagines, describe how they  

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:44.000
evolved, one from the other.  i.e., organisms which are very  

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
similar to one another must be more closely related evolutionarily,   

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:53.000
and conversely, those that appear very differently from one another,   

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:58.000
morphologically, must be far more distantly related to one another.   

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:02.000
In fact, these kinds of morphologic extrapolations can be very  

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.000
misleading.  So here,  for example, are two kinds of eyes.   

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:11.000
 The top eye is a Drysophila eye  

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:14.000
which, to state the obvious,  looks a lot different from our eyes,   

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:18.000
which is that the chordate eyes shown the bottom.   

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Totally different.  Our rods and cones face backwards,   

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.000
the Drysophila Arthropod eyes, the light sensors face forward.   

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
Everything is different.  And on the basis of that,   

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
you would say that these two organisms are independent  

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
evolutionary inventions,  that they've been invented on two  

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:37.000
occasions, and that they have no relatedness, one to the  

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:41.000
other, at all.  But I will tell you an extraordinary  

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:45.000
experiment.  You can take,  there's a master gene that controls  

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:50.000
eye development in the fly,  Drosophila.  It's called eyeless,   

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:55.000
if you knock it out then the eye doesn't develop at all.   

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:59.000
And you can take out of the mouse,  what is apparently a related gene  

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:04.000
called small eye,  so the fly gene is called eyeless  

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:09.000
and the mouse gene is called small eye.  And you can put the small-eyed  

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:13.000
gene into the Drosophila genome,  in a fly that lacks the eyeless gene.   

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:18.000
 So here we're talking about two  

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:22.000
different genes.  The fly gene is called eyeless,   

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.000
the mammalian gene, at least in mouse, is called small eye.   

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:30.000
If you knock out this gene in the fly genome, and replace it with this  

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.000
gene, you get a perfectly normal Drosophila eye.   

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.000
It's extraordinary.  Or you can do the following,   

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.000
you can arrange it so that the mouse small eye gene is expressed  

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.000
ectopically.  When I say ectopically,   

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:51.000
I mean that it's expressed in the wrong place, at the wrong time.   

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:56.000
